Bellabeat Case Study

Introduction and background

Bellabeat specializes in producing advanced technology products designed specifically for womens health needs.

The objective of this case study is to examine usage data of smart devices, with the aim of obtaining a better understanding of how customers utilize these devices and identifying patterns that can be leveraged to shape Bellabeats marketing approach

Stakeholders: Bellabeat Team

Urka Sren: Bellabeats cofounder and Chief Creative Officer Sando Mur: Mathematician and Bellabeats cofounder; key member of the Bellabeat executive team Bellabeat marketing analytics team

Ask Phase

Business task: Analyze smart device usage data in order to gain insight into how consumers use non-Bellabeat smart devices. Then apply these insights and trends into Bellabeats customers and marketing strategy.

Prepare Phase

For this case study we will use the dataset FitBit Fitness Tracker Data made available by Mobius.

The dataset contains personal fitness tracker from thirty FitBit users and includes information about daily activity, steps, and heart rate that can be used to explore users habits.

The dataset contains 18 different Excel documents tracking different variables. Data is organized in a long format since the consumer ID value repeats itself in the first column.

Licensing, privacy and accessibility

By checking the metadata of our dataset, we can verify that it is indeed open-source. The creator of the dataset has relinquished all copyright and related rights to the work worldwide, thus dedicating it to the public domain. This allows for the free copying, modification, distribution, and performance of the work, including for commercial purposes, without requiring prior permission.

Bias and integrity of the data

Given the size limitation of our sample (30 users) and the absence of any demographic information, there is a risk of encountering a sampling bias. We cannot be certain that the sample is truly reflective of the entire population. Furthermore, the dataset is not up-to-date and the survey period was restricted to only 2 months, adding to the potential limitations. To address these concerns, we will adopt an operational approach in our case study.

Process phase

I will use the RStudio tool for this case study due to its capacity for data cleaning and preparation, statistical analysis and visualization.

What does this tell us about how this sample of peoples activities?

We can see that the average number of steps per days is 7638, lower than the 10K usually steps recommended for a healthy lifestyle.

With regards to the average of sleep hours per night, that figure is close to 7 hours (419 minutes). The recommended amount of sleep hours of an adult is 7 to 9 hours.

Hence our consumers are on the lower band of both recommended number of steps per day and hours of sleep.

Plotting a few explorations

Whats the relationship between steps taken in a day and burned calories? How could this help inform the customer segments that we can market to?

Lets examine the following correlations:

Daily Steps vs Calories

ggplot(Activity, aes(x = Calories, y = TotalSteps)) +
  geom_point(size = 3, alpha = 0.5) +
  geom_smooth(method = "lm", se = FALSE) +
  labs(x = "Total Steps", y = "Calories", title = "Daily Steps vs Calories") +
  coord_cartesian(xlim = c(0, 5000), ylim = c(0, 30000)) +
  theme_minimal() +
  theme(
    plot.title = element_text(size = 16, face = "bold", hjust = 0.5),
    axis.title = element_text(size = 14),
    panel.grid = element_line(color = "gray", linetype = "dotted")
  )
## `geom_smooth()` using formula = 'y ~ x'

As expected, there is a positive correlation between the number of steps taken per day and the number of burned calories. The higher the physical activity the more calories are burned.

Consumers Activity levels

In the absence of demographic variables in our sample, we aim to classify users based on their activity level using the available data. We can group users into different categories by considering their daily step count. Therefore, we propose to determine the type of users based on their activity level, which can be classified as follows:

Sedentary: Less than 5,000 steps daily Low active: About 5,000 to 7,499 steps daily Somewhat active: About 7,500 to 9,999 steps daily Active: More than 10,000 steps daily *Highly active: More than 12,500 steps daily

Source: Medicinenet.com

Lets look at the average steps per user ID:

daily_average_steps <- Steps %>%
  group_by(Id) %>%
  summarise(mean_daily_steps = mean(StepTotal))
            

head(daily_average_steps)
## # A tibble: 6  2
##           Id mean_daily_steps
##        <dbl>            <dbl>
## 1 1503960366           12117.
## 2 1624580081            5744.
## 3 1644430081            7283.
## 4 1844505072            2580.
## 5 1927972279             916.
## 6 2022484408           11371.
user_activity <- daily_average_steps %>%
  mutate(user_type = case_when(
    mean_daily_steps < 5000 ~ "sedentary",
    mean_daily_steps >= 5000 & mean_daily_steps < 7499 ~ "lightly active", 
    mean_daily_steps >= 7500 & mean_daily_steps < 9999 ~ "fairly active", 
    mean_daily_steps >= 10000 ~ "active",
    mean_daily_steps >= 12500 ~ "highly active"
  ))

head(user_activity)

Lets now convert the above data into percentages:

library(dplyr)

user_activity_perc <- user_activity %>%
  group_by(user_type) %>%
  summarise(count = n()) %>%
  mutate(percentage = count / sum(count) * 100)

head(user_activity_perc)
## # A tibble: 4  3
##   user_type      count percentage
##   <chr>          <int>      <dbl>
## 1 active             7       21.2
## 2 fairly active      9       27.3
## 3 lightly active     9       27.3
## 4 sedentary          8       24.2

This distribution of physical activity levels suggests that the majority of users in this dataset are not highly physically active, as evidenced by the relatively low percentage of users in the active and highly active(none) categories. However, the fact that a larger percentage of users fall into the fairly active and lightly active categories is encouraging, as it suggests that many users are engaging in at least some physical activity.

Based on the activity levels of the users, we can infer that all types of users use smart devices.

Lets now create a pie chart to better visualize the user activity distribution.

library(dplyr)
library(ggplot2)

# create blue color scale
colors <- c("lightblue", "darkblue", "steelblue", "cornflowerblue", "navyblue")

# create pie chart with different colors for each user type
ggplot(user_activity_perc, aes(x = "", y = percentage, fill = user_type)) +
  geom_bar(width = 1, stat = "identity", color = "white") +
  geom_text(aes(label = paste0(round(percentage), "%")), position = position_stack(vjust = 0.5)) +
  coord_polar(theta = "y") +
  scale_fill_manual(values = colors) +
  theme_void()

Act

Based on everything we have seen before, some key findings are:

  • **Our users are on the lower band of both steps/day and hours slept per day. It would be highly advisable to increase these two parameters to promoto a healthy lifestyle for users.*

  • There is a correlation observed between the daily steps taken and the calories burned, as well as between the total time spent in bed and minutes asleep.

  • The majority of users (51%) are not very active physically.

  • Users are most active between 17.00 to 19.00h.

Business reccomendations:

  1. The datasets provided only offer a limited sample size and lack demographic information, such as age and gender. Considering the target audience is women, I recommend developing marketing strategies specifically tailored to young and professional women.

  2. Based on our analysis, it is apparent that users are not getting an adequate amount of sleep, specifically less than 8 hours a day. To address this issue, we recommend implementing a feature that allows users to set their desired bedtime and receive a notification a few minutes before, helping them prepare for sleep. Additionally, we can offer helpful resources such as breathing exercises, podcasts featuring relaxing music, and various sleep techniques to assist customers in improving their sleep habits.

  3. Expand the health tracking capabilities of the smartwatch to include features specifically designed for womens health, such as menstrual cycle tracking, fertility monitoring, and pregnancy support. These features provide valuable insights and support, helping women manage their overall well-being and fitness goals.

  4. Implement a reward and incentive system within the smartwatch ecosystem. Users can earn virtual badges, unlock achievements, and receive discounts on fitness gear or other relevant products based on their activity levels and milestones. This gamification element adds an element of fun and motivation to regular physical activity.

  5. Create a range of **smartwatch designs specifically targeted to women*, offering a variety of colors, straps, and customizable watch faces. By catering to individual preferences and style, the smartwatch becomes an appealing accessory, encouraging consistent usage and making physical activity a fashionable experience.
